  <h2>1. IPQmedia (ours, and here is the bias)</h2>
  <p>
    We run paid ads for architecture firms, mostly Facebook and Instagram, then our team
    calls, qualifies and books every lead directly onto the firm's calendar. The model is
    pay per performance: you fund the ad spend and pay us for qualified consultations
    that show up, not a monthly retainer for activity. We take one firm per market, which
    means we regularly turn people down. Either integrity or a supply problem, depending
    on your mood.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you do residential work, the engine points at homeowners planning a high-end build or renovation, the buyer mapped in <a href="/marketing-for-residential-architects">marketing for residential architects</a>. If you do commercial, same engine, different aim: developers and business owners, proof-heavy creative, patient retargeting through the long sales cycle. How the machine works end to end is laid out in <a href="/lead-generation-for-architects">lead generation for architects</a>, and the case for the channel itself in <a href="/meta-ads-for-architects">Meta ads for architects</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wrong for: firms that want brand strategy, a new website, or to learn marketing
    in-house, because we do not sell any of that. Also wrong if your market is already
    taken.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Architect Marketing Institute (archmarketing.org)</h2>
  <p>
    Training, frameworks and coaching for architects doing their own marketing, including AIA-approved webinars. Their content moat is real: they rank for nearly every architecture-marketing search there is, including a few we would like back. How that game works is mapped in <a href="/seo-for-architects">SEO for architects</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Right for: solo practitioners and small firms with more time than budget. The honest
    limit: you are the one doing the work. A course does not run campaigns, and the
    marketing still has to happen between deadlines, which is exactly where it went
    missing the first time.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Archmark (archmark.co)</h2>
  <p>
    A husband-and-wife-founded agency working exclusively with architects since 2016,
    built around the StoryBrand messaging framework. Branding, websites, positioning,
    plus coaching.
  </p>
  <p>
    Right for: firms whose problem is "nobody understands what makes us different," not
    "the phone is not ringing." The honest limit: clearer messaging does not generate
    demand by itself. It makes the demand you create convert better, which matters only
    once you are creating some.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Third &amp; Arch (thirdandarch.com)</h2>
  <p>
    A Philadelphia agency doing brand identity, websites, SEO and digital marketing for architecture, engineering and construction firms, with a strong portfolio of architecture-specific sites.
  </p>
  <p>
    Right for: firms whose site genuinely embarrasses them in front of clients. The honest limit: a better website converts the visitors you already have, it does not manufacture new ones. That filter-versus-source problem is the whole of <a href="/website-design-for-architects">website design for architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Smartegies (smartegies.com)</h2>
  <p>
    An Atlanta-area consultancy for the AEC industry: strategic planning, marketing
    training and recruiting, with a client roster that runs toward the Kimley-Horns and
    Michael Baker Internationals of the world.
  </p>
  <p>
    Right for: large commercial firms with a business development team to organize and enterprise pursuits to win. The honest limit: it is consulting, not a demand engine, and if you are a five-person studio it is a beautifully tailored suit in someone else's size. The buyer it fits best is described in <a href="/marketing-for-commercial-architects">marketing for commercial architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Reputation Ink (rep-ink.com)</h2>
  <p>
    A Jacksonville PR and content shop for expertise-driven firms, AEC among them, alongside law and B2B services. Media placements, awards, speaking slots, thought leadership. The written version of that authority, the kind you own on your own site, is <a href="/content-marketing-for-architects">content marketing for architects</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Right for: established firms that need their expertise visible where decision-makers look. The honest limit: press is proof, not a pipeline. It compounds and it opens doors, and it rarely books next month's consultations. Where that proof actually fits is covered in <a href="/pr-and-press-for-architects">PR and press for architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Nover Marketing (novermarketing.com)</h2>
  <p>
    A Colorado agency serving the broader building industry: architects, engineers,
    contractors, design-build firms and manufacturers. Strategy, branding, websites, SEO,
    content and paid ads.
  </p>
  <p>
    Right for: a building-industry company that wants one competent vendor for a bit of
    everything. The honest limit is the breadth itself: architecture firms are one of
    several industries they serve, and undivided attention is the thing a specialist
    exists to sell. They also publish a best-agencies list of their own. Noticing a
    pattern here is left as an exercise.
  </p>

  <h2>The option people try before any of these: lead marketplaces</h2>
  <p>
    Houzz Pro, Thumbtack and friends are not agencies, but they are where many firms
    spend their first marketing dollar, so they belong on the page. You are buying access
    to people who raised a hand on a platform. The structural catch: the same lead is
    often sold to several pros at once, so you are racing everyone else who paid, and the
    fastest reply tends to beat the best portfolio.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some firms make marketplaces work with ruthless follow-up speed. Most architects we
    talk to tried one, got ghosted a lot, and left. Renting access to someone else's
    audience is not the same thing as owning a pipeline, and the gap between those two is
    most of what this site is about.
  </p>

  <h2>A few honest answers</h2>
  <h3>Who is the best marketing agency for architects?</h3>
  <p>
    The one that fixes the part of your growth that is actually broken. For a steady
    volume of qualified client consultations we think it is us, and you should discount
    any answer a company gives about itself. For learning it yourself it is Architect
    Marketing Institute, for brand clarity Archmark, for a site rebuild Third &amp; Arch.
    Anyone who answers this question without asking about your situation first is
    selling, not advising.
  </p>
  <h3>How much does a marketing agency cost for an architecture firm?</h3>
  <p>
    Specialist retainers typically start in the low four figures a month and climb with
    scope. Courses run from hundreds to a few thousand total. Pay-per-performance models
    like ours charge for delivered results instead of time spent. The more useful math:
    compare those numbers to one signed project. For most firms a single commission
    covers a year of marketing, so the real question is not the sticker, it is who
    carries the risk if nothing comes back.
  </p>
  <h3>Should an architecture firm hire an agency or do marketing in-house?</h3>
  <p>
    Do it in-house if you have more time than budget and someone in the firm genuinely
    wants to own it. Hire it out if your hours bill better on buildings, which for most
    principals they do. The trap is the middle: buying a course nobody finishes, or
    hiring a cheap generalist who treats an architecture firm like a restaurant with
    blueprints. Either path works done properly. The half-versions are what waste the
    year.
  </p>
  <h3>What should you ask an agency before signing?</h3>
  <p>
    Three questions expose most of them. Who exactly do you serve? A real specialist
    names the buyer, the project type and the market; a generalist says "businesses like
    yours." Who carries the risk if it does not work? Retainers put it on you,
    performance models put it on the agency. And who does the work after the sales call?
    The person pitching you is often the last senior person you will ever speak to.
  </p>

  <h2>Diagnose first, hire second</h2>
  <p>
    Every entry above is the right answer to a different question, which is the part the
    weighted-scoring lists skip on purpose. Work out whether your problem is knowledge,
    clarity, conversion or volume, then hire the specialist for that problem and hold
    them to exactly it.
  </p>
  <p>
    And if the diagnosis is volume, the phone that should be ringing and is not, that is
    the one problem we built our whole company around.
  </p>
